# 2️⃣ Interview Problems Using Bit Manipulation

---

# Problem 1

Find the Unique Element

Array:

```text
2 1 4 1 2
```

Every number appears twice except one.

Find it.

---

### Brute Force

Nested loops.

```text
O(n²)
```

---

### Smart Solution

Use XOR.

Because:

```text
1 ^ 1 = 0

2 ^ 2 = 0
```

Only:

```text
4
```

remains.

---

### Dry Run

```text
2 ^ 1 ^ 4 ^ 1 ^ 2

=

2 ^ 2

^

1 ^ 1

^

4

=

0 ^ 0 ^ 4

=

4
```

Amazing!

---

# Problem 2

Check if Number is Even

Instead of:

```cpp
n % 2 == 0
```

Use:

```cpp
(n & 1)
```

---

Why?

Binary:

Even:

```text
1000

Ends with 0
```

Odd:

```text
1001

Ends with 1
```

So:

```cpp
n & 1
```

checks the last bit.

---

# Mental Model

Last switch:

```text
0

Even

1

Odd
```

---

# Problem 3

Power of Two

Examples:

```text
2

4

8

16

32
```

Binary:

```text
2 = 0010

4 = 0100

8 = 1000
```

Notice:

Only ONE bit is ON.

---

Trick:

```cpp
n & (n-1)
```

If answer becomes:

```text
0
```

Then number is power of two.

---

# Why?

Example:

```text
8

1000
```

7:

```text
0111
```

AND:

```text
1000

0111

----

0000
```

---

# Problem 4

Swap Without Temporary Variable

Normally:

```cpp
temp = a;

a = b;

b = temp;
```

Using XOR:

```cpp
a ^= b;

b ^= a;

a ^= b;
```

Interviewers sometimes ask this.

(Although using `std::swap()` is preferred in real code.)

